player_news.title: Brandon Aubrey - Away from team
player_news.description: Aubrey has yet to rejoin the Cowboys at training camp following the birth of his first child, Calvin Watkins of The Dallas Morning News reports.
player_news.analysis: The kicker played in Sunday's preseason game against the Rams, converting four of five field-goal attempts with his only miss coming from 65 yards out, but he immediately jumped on a plane afterward to be with his wife. Aubrey is coming off a record-setting rookie season in which he led the NFL in made field goals with 36 and points with 157, and he should again be one of the most productive kicking options in the league in 2024 with a Dak Prescott-led offense at his back.

player_news.title: Jerry Jeudy - Participates in 7-on-7 drills
player_news.description: Jeudy (leg) is participating in 7-on-7 drills at practice Wednesday, Zac Jackson of The Athletic reports.
player_news.analysis: Jeudy is on the field for 7-on-7 work for just the second time this training camp, as he's otherwise bounced between limited participation and time on the sideline due to a lingering leg injury. Scott Petrak of the Elyria Chronicle-Telegram reports that Jeudy also handled 1-on-1 reps in full pads Wednesday, so it looks like he's now healthy. Jeudy could thus be in line to make his Browns debut during Saturday's preseason game against the Vikings, though Cleveland elected to hold key starters including Deshaun Watson, Amari Cooper and David Njoku out from last week's exhibition opener against the Packers.

player_news.title: Drew Lock - Could play Saturday
player_news.description: Coach Brian Daboll said Tuesday that Lock (hip) is doing "a lot better" and could be active for Saturday's preseason game against the Texans, Dan Salomone of the Giants' official site reports.
player_news.analysis: Lock said he fully expects to be ready for Week 1, per Pat Leonard of the New York Daily News. The backup QB suffered a bone contusion and strained oblique during New York's preseason opener against the Lions, but it doesn't appear he'll be sidelined too long. Until Lock returns to practice, though, No. 3 quarterback Tommy DeVito figures to benefit from increased reps.

player_news.title: Dak Prescott - Practicing in full Wednesday
player_news.description: Prescott (ankle) will be a full participant in Wednesday's joint practice with the Rams, Jon Machota of The Athletic reports.
player_news.analysis: Prescott was given a precautionary day off last Friday due to ankle soreness, but the issue is no longer hampering him. If the Cowboys elect to play key starters during Saturday's road preseason game against the Raiders, Prescott will thus be in line to start after having missed the team's exhibition opener against Los Angeles. Prescott is still working without star wideout CeeDee Lamb (holdout) at practice, as the No. 1 receiver remains away from team activities amid an ongoing contract dispute.

player_news.title: Dak Prescott To Return To Practice On Wednesday
player_news.description: Dallas Cowboys quarterback Dak Prescott (ankle) was scheduled to take part in Tuesday's mock game. "If we were in pads today, he would practice," head coach Mike McCarthy said. Prescott will then return to a joint practice on Wednesday with the Los Angeles Rams. The 31-year-old has had some residual ankle soreness crop up this summer, and although the Cowboys held him out of the preseason opener on Sunday, he's in no danger of missing the start of the 2024 regular season. Depending on how his ankle responds in his return to practice, Prescott could suit up and play a few series in the second preseason game this Saturday against the Las Vegas Raiders. Prescott had the finest season of his career in 2023, but his lack of rushing production keeps him out of the elite tier of QB1s.

player_news.title: Tanner Brown - Let go by Rams
player_news.description: The Rams waived Brown on Tuesday.
player_news.analysis: Brown didn't attempt a field goal in Sunday's preseason game against the Cowboys, while Joshua Karty made both of his field-goal attempts and converted his lone extra-point attempt. Should he clear waivers, Brown will look to catch onto a team in need of a kicker. He converted 22 of 23 field-goal attempts and converted all 42 of his extra-point attempts in his final collegiate season with Stanford in 2022

player_news.title: Hamze El-Zayat - Reaches injury settlement
player_news.description: The Jets waived El-Zayat (undisclosed) from injured reserve with an injury settlement Tuesday, Aaron Wilson of KPRC 2 Houston reports.
player_news.analysis: El-Zayat reverted to the Jets' IR on Thursday after being waived with an undisclosed injury designation Wednesday. Now that a settlement has been reached, the 24-year-old wide receiver will be able to try out for another team once he is healthy.

player_news.title: Sam Darnold - Positioned as starter for 2024
player_news.description: Darnold is poised to start the Vikings' Sept. 8 season opener versus the Giants and could be in position to serve as the team's top quarterback for the entire 2024 campaign after 10th overall pick J.J. McCarthy (knee) underwent season-ending meniscus surgery Wednesday, Kevin Seifert of ESPN.com reports.
player_news.analysis: Darnold will dominate the remainder of first-team reps in training camp and preseason action for the Vikings, while Nick Mullens moves up a spot on the depth chart to the No. 2 role. The team could explore adding more options to the quarterback room with McCarthy done for the season, but if Darnold is able to competently command the offense, he now has a clear path to a season-long starting gig. There's no guarantee that Darnold -- who has never suited up for more than 13 games in a season in his seven-year career -- can accomplish that task, but he is arguably in the best environment he's seen in the NFL. No. 1 wide receiver Justin Jefferson may be the most reliable target in the league, Jordan Addison appears primed to build upon a productive rookie campaign and T.J. Hockenson (knee) is a premier tight end option, when healthy. The Vikings offense could have some downside if Addision faces a suspension for his offseason DUI arrest, or if Hockenson's recovery from an ACL tear stretches into the later portion of the regular season, but in fantasy leagues that allow for multiple starting quarterbacks, Darnold now looks like an intriguing late-round flier.

player_news.title: Sam Darnold Set To Start In Week 1
player_news.description: With Minnesota Vikings rookie first-round quarterback J.J. McCarthy (knee) scheduled to under knee surgery, Sam Darnold is now squarely in line to be the team's opening-day starting QB in Week 1 against the New York Giants. Even if McCarthy was fully healthy, Darnold was expected to open as Minnesota's starting signal-caller, but the 27-year-old former first-rounder should have a longer leash now, especially if McCarthy needs a full meniscus repair. Darnold has been handling most of the first-team reps in training camp, and now he'll get even more with McCarthy sidelined. Fantasy managers aren't going to be expecting much from Darnold after he was a bust with the New York Jets, but he could pass as a serviceable low-end QB2 in superflex leagues with the best supporting cast on offense he's ever had in his career.

player_news.title: Zack Annexstad - Clears waivers
player_news.description: Annexstad (undisclosed) cleared waivers Tuesday per the NFL's transaction log.
player_news.analysis: Tampa Bay waived Annexstad Tuesday with a non-football injury designation, and no other team opted to pick him up during the last waiver period. He'll need to return to action soon to have any chance at making a 53-man roster for 2024.

player_news.title: Andy Dalton - Cleared from injury
player_news.description: Dalton (quadriceps) returned to practice Wednesday, David Newton of ESPN.com Reports.
player_news.analysis: Dalton injured his quad Aug. 1 and was expected to need a couple of weeks to recover. The veteran quarterback should have a firm grasp on the Panthers' backup job to starter Bryce Young.

player_news.title: Andy Dalton (quad) returns to practice Wednesday
player_news.description: Panthers QB Andy Dalton (quad) has returned to practice Wednesday.
player_news.analysis: Dalton has missed the last two weeks with a quad injury. He will likely see time in the second preseason game, barring any setbacks in practice.

player_news.title: Ramiz Ahmed - Let go by Washington
player_news.description: The Commanders waived Ahmed on Tuesday.
player_news.analysis: Ahmed signed with the Commanders back in June and spent time competing with Riley Patterson at placekicker in training camp, but he's now been cut to make room for veteran wideout Martavis Bryant. The last time Ahmed logged NFL action was 2022, when he played one game with the Packers.

player_news.title: Zach Wilson impressing HC with his aggressiveness
player_news.description: Zach Wilson is reportedly impressing Sean Payton with his aggressiveness.
player_news.analysis: Payton said Wilson's reps against the Colts were very good. He should continue to see more reps the rest of the preseason as he competes for a role in the Broncos quarterback room.

player_news.title: Robert Burns - Goes back to PUP list
player_news.description: Atlanta placed Burns (undisclosed) on its reserve-PUP list Tuesday, Aaron Wilson of KPRC 2 Houston reports.
player_news.analysis: The Falcons waived Burns on Monday after he failed a physical, but now he's back with the team since no other club claimed him during the last waiver period. Until he's healthy enough to play again, Carlos Washington could see increased reps at practice.

player_news.title: Jake Browning To Miss Time With A Rib Injury
player_news.description: Cincinnati Bengals quarterback Jake Browning (ribs) is expected to miss time with a rib injury, according to head coach Zac Taylor. Browning filled in admirably for Joe Burrow when the latter missed a large chunk of last season with a wrist injury, prompting the team to re-sign him as their backup quarterback. Veteran Logan Woodside and undrafted free agent Rocky Lombardi will be the quarterbacks under center when the Bengals travel to Chicago for their second preseason game.

player_news.title: Jake Browning - Nursing rib injury
player_news.description: Browning did not participate at practice Tuesday due to a rib injury he sustained during Saturday's preseason game versus the Buccaneers, Ben Baby of ESPN reports.
player_news.analysis: The exact severity of the issue is unclear, but Coach Zac Taylor said Tuesday that Browning would "miss some time." In his stead, Logan Woodside may see more opportunities to impress during drills.

player_news.title: Jordan Love Won’t Play Against Broncos
player_news.description: Green Bay Packers quarterback Sean Clifford will start this week's preseason game versus the Denver Broncos on Sunday as Jordan Love won't play, head coach Matt LaFleur announced on Wednesday at training camp. Rookie Michael Pratt will serve as the backup quarterback on Sunday against the Broncos. After completing each of his two passes for 63 yards and a touchdown in last week's preseason opener against the Cleveland Browns, Love will take a seat this weekend before presumably returning to action for a regular-season tune-up against the Baltimore Ravens on Aug. 24. In an ascending Packers offense, the 25-year-old star signal-caller has his sights set on taking another leap forward in 2024 after closing as fantasy's overall QB5 in points per game (19.4) over 17 appearances in 2023 during his first year as Green Bay's full-time starter.

player_news.title: Jordan Love - Not likely to play this week
player_news.description: Packers head coach Matt LaFleur said that Love isn't expected to play in Sunday's preseason game against the Broncos, Rob Demovsky of ESPN.com reports.
player_news.analysis: LaFleur noted that he's planning to start Sean Clifford, then use rookie Michael Pratt as the second quarterback. Love played one drive in a 23-10 exhibition win over Cleveland on Saturday, connecting with Dontayvion Wicks for a 65-yard touchdown on the third snap of the game.

player_news.title: Tyler Boyd absent from practice Wednesday
player_news.description: Tyler Boyd was absent from practice on Wednesday with the Titans.
player_news.analysis: It is unclear if Boyd is injured or if he got the day off. There should be an update when available on his status.

player_news.title: Hendon Hooker - Trending toward playing Saturday
player_news.description: Coach Dan Campbell said Wednesday that Hooker (concussion) has "a good chance to play" in Saturday's preseason contest against the Chiefs, Tim Twentyman of the Lions' official site reports.
player_news.analysis: Hooker suffered a concussion during Detroit's preseason opener, but he looks to be on track for a return during the team's second exhibition context. The 2023 third-round pick, who didn't log any game reps as a rookie, completed 5 of 9 pass attempts for 39 yards versus the Giants last week. He also rushed four times for 39 yards but suffered the head injury due to a hit while scrambling. Nate Sudfeld started versus New York and appears to currently be in the lead for the backup spot behind Jared Goff, but Hooker still has time to impress before Detroit's regular-season opener against the Rams on September 8.

player_news.title: Michael Pratt - Second in line for sunday
player_news.description: Pratt will follow Sean Clifford on Sunday against the Broncos, Bill Huber of Sports Illustrated reports.
player_news.analysis: Pratt and Clifford will continue their competition for the backup job to starter Jordan Love, in the Packers' second preseason game. The former completed five of seven passes for 46 yards against the Browns last Saturday.

player_news.title: Ja'Marr Chase - Misses first practice of camp
player_news.description: Coach Zac Taylor said Tuesday that Chase (undisclosed), who missed practice for this first time this training camp, is a situation the Bengals will monitor day-to-day, Ben Baby of ESPN.com reports.
player_news.analysis: Chase has yet to actually participate in practice in training camp, but until Tuesday  he'd been present every day while in street clothes. It remains to be seen whether Chase's absence is related to an injury sustained during private workouts, a personal matter, or his ongoing contract dispute. In any event, it's a new development as the star wide receiver's 'hold-in' continues. The Bengals should provide further clarity about Chase's status in the near future.

player_news.title: Justin Herbert Still In Walking Boot
player_news.description: Los Angeles Chargers quarterback Justin Herbert (foot) is still in a walking boot. It was reported on August 1 that Herbert would wear a boot on his right foot for approximately two weeks while he recovers from a plantar fascia injury. Now that the two-week mark is almost upon us, fantasy managers will be eager to see Herbert walking under his own power again. Herbert is looking to bounce back after a down season in 2023. Injuries and poor team organization limited Herbert to 3,134 passing yards and 20 touchdowns in 13 games. The Chargers have revamped their wide receiver core and will need Herbert to perform at a high level to support the inexperienced pass catchers. Fantasy managers interested in rostering Herbert or any Chargers skill players should closely monitor this situation.

player_news.title: Bryan Thompson - Waived/injured by Buffalo
player_news.description: The Bills waived Thompson (hamstring) with an injury designation Tuesday.
player_news.analysis: Thompson will revert to Buffalo's injured reserve if he goes unclaimed on waivers. He spent time on the team's practice squad last season after going undrafted out of Arizona State.

player_news.title: Jalen McMillan - Wears red non-contact jersey Monday
player_news.description: McMillan was dealing with what head coach Todd Bowles labeled "general soreness" Monday, leading to the rookie wearing a red non-contact jersey in practice, Scott Smith of the team's official site reports.
player_news.analysis: McMillan continued to make a strong case for the No. 3 receiver job in Saturday's preseason win over the Bengals, recording two receptions for 23 yards. However, it appears McMillan's first taste of professional on-field action also left him a bit worse for wear in the short term, and it remains to be seen if if the rookie will be able to participate in the first day of joint practices with the Jaguars on Wednesday.

player_news.title: Sean Clifford - Will see snaps first
player_news.description: Clifford will start Sunday's game against the Broncos, according to head coach Matt LaFleur, Bill Huber of Sports Illustrated reports.
player_news.analysis: Clifford will be followed by Michael Pratt with Jordan Love set to get the night off. The Penn State product completed 10 of 19 pass attempts for 111 yards in a 23-10 win over the Browns on Saturday.

player_news.title: Lawrence Cager - Now nursing groin injury
player_news.description: Cager (groin) did not practice Tuesday due to a groin injury, Art Stapleton of The Bergen Record reports.
player_news.analysis: Cager was sidelined due to a hamstring injury to begin training camp, and upon returning to practice Sunday he quickly suffered a groin issue. The 26-year-old is competing for a depth role at tight end, but he's had difficult staying on the field so far. Cager's injury could keep him out of Saturday's preseason contest on the road against Houston.

player_news.title: Trent Pennix - Goes on IR
player_news.description: Pennix (groin) reverted to the Colts' injured reserve Tuesday after going unclaimed off waivers, per the NFL transaction log.
player_news.analysis: Pennix sustained a groin injury in Sunday's preseason bout against Denver. He was waived/injured by Indianapolis on Monday, but he was moved to IR the next day after not being claimed off waivers by another team. Pennix will now be forced to sit for the entire 2024 season unless he reaches an injury settlement with the Colts.

player_news.title: Kyle Trask - Not locked into No. 2 job
player_news.description: Head coach Todd Bowles said Monday that Trask and John Wolford are still in competition for the No. 2 quarterback job, Scott Smith of the team's official site reports.
player_news.analysis: Trask has been the presumptive No. 2 quarterback this offseason and training camp after filling that role in 2023, but Bowles is apparently making the University of Florida product earn that slotting again this summer. The two quarterbacks each played a half in Saturday night's preseason-opening win over the Bengals and put up comparable numbers, so the competition could last through the entirety of the preseason slate.

player_news.title: Tucker Kraft (pec) returns to 11-on-11 drills Tuesday
player_news.description: Tucker Kraft got back into 11-on-11 work at practice on Tuesday.
player_news.analysis: Kraft is continuing to work his way back from pectoral injury/surgery. He said he's full speed ahead now and should be fully healthy by the start of the season.

player_news.title: Hassan Hall - Gets opportunity in desert
player_news.description: The Cardinals signed Hall to a contract Tuesday.
player_news.analysis: Hall resurfaces in Arizona after having been cut by the Chiefs back in June. As a rookie last season, Hall spent time on the practice squads of the Giants, Cardinals and Browns. Now, he returns to Arizona to continue his development.

player_news.title: John Kelly - Picked up by Baltimore
player_news.description: The Ravens signed Kelly to a contract Tuesday.
player_news.analysis: Kelly spent most of last season on Cleveland's practice squad but didn't suit up for a regular-season game with the team. The 2018 sixth-round pick now has a chance to compete for a deep depth role in Baltimore, with his best-case scenario likely to be a spot on the practice squad again.

player_news.title: Mike Evans returns to practice Wednesday
player_news.description: Mike Evans returned to practice on Wednesday with the Buccaneers.
player_news.analysis: Evans had left practice for a bit before he returned shortly after. It was unclear if an injury occurred as he walked off the field himself, but he is all good.

player_news.title: Mike Evans Returns To Practice After Exiting
player_news.description: Tampa Bay Buccaneers wide receiver Mike Evans left Wednesday's joint practice with the Jacksonville Jaguars early, but he was able to return to the session later on. Evans initially walked off the field without assistance, so there's no reason for fantasy managers to be concerned with what sounds like a false alarm here. The 31-year-old Pro Bowl wideout has entrenched himself as a fantasy stalwart throughout his career, and while his role in Tampa Bay as quarterback Baker Mayfield's primary deep threat means his floor might not be as high as those being selected around him, Evans' ceiling remains among fantasy's highest after he totaled 36 deep targets and 13 touchdowns in 17 games for the Bucs last season. He's a fringe WR1/2 option in drafts this summer.

player_news.title: Mike Evans leaves practice early Wednesday
player_news.description: Mike Evans left practice early on Wednesday and did not return.
player_news.analysis: Evans was able to walk off the field without assistance. There should be an update on his status when available.

player_news.title: Frank Darby - Moves to IR
player_news.description: Darby (undisclosed) reverted to the 49ers' reserve/injured list Tuesday after clearing waivers, per the NFL transaction log.
player_news.analysis: Darby will now be forced to sit out for the 2024 season unless he reaches an injury settlement with San Francisco. The 2021 sixth-round wide receiver has played in 16 regular-season games across his three-year career as a member of the Falcons, operating mostly on special teams.

player_news.title: Diontae Johnson Day-To-Day With Groin Strain
player_news.description: Carolina Panthers wide receiver Diontae Johnson (groin) is dealing with a mild groin strain and is considered day-to-day, head coach Dave Canales told reporters at Wednesday's practice during training camp. Soft-tissue injuries always have a chance to linger, but it would likely be an overreaction at this point to significantly alter Johnson's standing in fantasy rankings based on this development. It remains to be seen if he'll be able to return to practice ahead of Saturday's preseason game against the visiting New York Jets. Without very much competition surrounding him in Carolina's receiving corps, Johnson figures to be the focal point of the Panthers' passing game in 2024 as quarterback Bryce Young's top target. The 27-year-old veteran wideout is a WR3 with WR2 upside in the second half of fantasy drafts this summer.

player_news.title: Diontae Johnson - Sidelined by groin strain
player_news.description: Panthers head coach Dave Canales said Johnson missed Wednesday's practice with a "mild groin strain," Alex Zietlow of The Charlotte Observer reports.
player_news.analysis: Aside from Wednesday, Johnson hasn't missed any notable practice time since the Panthers traded for him in March, with most reports from training camp noting that the 28-year-old receiver has seen a steady flow of targets from quarterback Bryce Young. Canales downplayed the severity of the groin strain, but it's probably safe to assume Johnson will miss Saturday's preseason game against the Jets.

player_news.title: Diontae Johnson has mild groin strain
player_news.description: Panthers coach Dave Canales said WR Diontae Johnson has a mild groin strain.
player_news.analysis: The injury held Johnson out of practice on Wednesday. It does not appear to be anything too serious.

player_news.title: J.J. McCarthy (meniscus) to miss rookie season
player_news.description: Minnesota Vikings rookie quarterback J.J. McCarthy will miss his entire rookie season after getting a meniscus repair after his injury in his NFL preseason debut last weekend.
player_news.analysis: McCarthy and his team have opted for the full repair for his meniscus, which will knock him out for the entire season but is likely better long-term for his health. Veteran QB Sam Darnold will officially be Minnesota's QB1 entering 2024, as the first-rounder McCarthy will take a medical redshirt and prepare for 2025. It is likely the Vikings will pick up at least one more veteran QB to contest for QB2 duties alongside QB Jaren Hall and Nick Mullens before the regular season begins.

player_news.title: J.J. McCarthy - Will miss entire rookie season
player_news.description: Vikings head coach Kevin O'Connell announced that McCarthy underwent season-ending surgery Wednesday to repair a torn meniscus in his right knee.
player_news.analysis: The Vikings announced Tuesday that McCarthy would require knee surgery, but at that time, the team seemed to be optimism that the rookie No. 10 overall pick might only need his meniscus trimmed, an operation would have allowed him to return in 2024. Instead, after McCarthy met with doctors for surgery Wednesday, the determination was made for the quarterback to undergo a full repair of the meniscus. With McCarthy's rookie season now completely wiped out, Sam Darnold is in position to start Week 1 under center for the Vikings, and potentially maintain a hold on the top spot on the depth chart for the entire 2024 campaign. The team could look to upgrade its depth at the position behind Darnold, with journeyman Nick Mullens and second-year quarterback Jaren Hall currently ranking as the Nos. 2 and 3 options, respectively.

player_news.title: J.J. McCarthy - Severity of knee injury TBD
player_news.description: McCarthy (knee) has a tear in his meniscus in his right knee and the severity of the injury will be determined once he undergoes surgery, Andrew Krammer of the Minneapolis Star Tribune reports.
player_news.analysis: McCarthy is set to miss extended time, but an exact timetable "will be something determined during the procedure," according to head coach Kevin O'Connell. If the quarterback is dealing with a small tear, he may be able to address it with a cleanup surgery, but a full repair would mean a longer recovery, Ben Goessling of the Minneapolis Star Tribune reports. O'Connell also added that the team will ultimately do "what's best for the long-term health of J.J."

player_news.title: Rashid Shaheed - Sheds non-contact jersey
player_news.description: Shaheed (hamstring) practiced in full Wednesday, Ross Jackson of WWL Louisiana reports.
player_news.analysis: Shaheed missed New Orleans' preseason opener due to a hamstring injury sustained Aug. 3, but it looks like he's now back to full health. That positions him to suit up for Sunday's road exhibition contest against the 49ers, assuming the Saints' starters take the field. Shaheed is primed for a key role on offense this season, both as New Orleans' primary punt and kick returner, and as the No. 2 receiver behind Chris Olave.

player_news.title: Zander Horvath - Waived by New Orleans
player_news.description: The Saints waived Horvath on Tuesday.
player_news.analysis: Horvath spent most of the offseason with New Orleans, but he'll now need to search for an opportunity to compete for a depth role elsewhere. The 2022 seventh-round pick appeared in 15 regular-season contests with the Chargers as a rookie, but he hasn't suited up for a game since.

player_news.title: DJ Moore (ankle/foot) back on practice field Wednesday
player_news.description: DJ Moore had his helmet back on and joined the wide receivers, who were waiting to get in during 11-on-11s at practice on Wednesday.
player_news.analysis: Moore limped off the field and had his right ankle/foot checked out by trainers. It turned out to be nothing too serious as he quickly returned back to the field.

player_news.title: DJ Moore limping with apparent ankle/foot injury
player_news.description: DJ Moore was limping off the field on Wednesday with an apparent ankle/foot injury.
player_news.analysis: Moore was getting his right ankle/foot looked at by the trainers on the side. There should be an update on his status when available. Moore is fresh off signing a four-year extension with the Bears.

player_news.title: Tyrone Tracy - Has low-ankle sprain
player_news.description: Tracy was diagnosed with a low right-ankle sprain after he got injured during Tuesday's practice, Ian Rapoport of NFL Network reports.
player_news.analysis: Initially, Tracy was believed to have suffered a serious injury because he needed an air cast on his lower right leg and was carted off the practice field before being taken to the Hospital for Special Surgery in Manhattan. After that visit, though, the rookie fifth-rounder was back in the team facility in meetings a few hours later, per Jordan Raanan of ESPN.com, with his lower right leg in a boot. Tracy's prognosis is week-to-week, which presumably will keep him sidelined for the Giants' final two preseason games but could allow him to be available Week 1 against the Vikings.

player_news.title: Tyrone Tracy thought to have sprained ankle
player_news.description: It appears Tyrone Tracy is thought to have sprained ankle and avoided a serious injury after he was carted off the field on Tuesday.
player_news.analysis: Tracy was carted off the practice field on Tuesday with what initially seemed like a more serious injury. It appears he may have avoided the best case scenario, though it is still a situation to monitor.

player_news.title: Tyler Lockett dealing with leg issue
player_news.description: Tyler Lockett did not do much at practice on Wednesday as he is dealing with a leg issue.
player_news.analysis: "He's got a little something going on in his leg right now but he's good. Tyler will be ready to roll," Seahawks coach Mike Macdonald said. It doesn't appear to be a serious injury.

player_news.title: Equanimeous St. Brown - Practices without contact
player_news.description: St. Brown (hamstring) participated in Tuesday's practice while wearing a red non-contact jersey, John Hendrix of SI.com reports.
player_news.analysis: St. Brown was held out of Saturday's preseason game against the Cardinals due to a hamstring injury he sustained in late July. The 2018 sixth-round wideout was able to return to practice Tuesday without engaging in contact, and he'll aim to be available for Sunday's preseason contest against San Francisco.

player_news.title: Dante Miller - Dealing with hamstring injury
player_news.description: Miller (hamstring) was limited at practice Tuesday, Dan Duggan of The Athletic reports.
player_news.analysis: Miller impressed during New York's preseason opener against the Lions, when he rushed 12 times for 63 yards and secured both of his targets for seven yards, but he's now dealing with a hamstring injury that could impact his status for Saturday's exhibition game against Houston. With Tyrone Tracy (ankle) having suffered a low-ankle sprain at practice Tuesday, Miller is facing an opportunity for increased reps if he can get healthy without missing much time.

player_news.title: Shane Buechele - Lands on injured reserve
player_news.description: The Bills placed Buechele (neck) on injured reserve Tuesday.
player_news.analysis: Buechele suffered a significant neck injury during Buffalo's preseason opener against the Bears. Unless he can reach an injury settlement with the team, Buechele will have to spend the entire 2024 campaign on IR with the Bills.

player_news.title: Payne Durham dealing with knee injury
player_news.description: Buccaneers coach Todd Bowles said TE Payne Durham sustained a knee injury in practice on Wednesday.
player_news.analysis: The severity of the injury is unclear for Durham. There should be an update on his status when available at some point later in the week.

player_news.title: Jahmyr Gibbs expected to be ready for Week 1, injury treated 'cautiously'
player_news.description: The hamstring injury Jahmyr Gibbs suffered is not considered significant, but the team will be very cautious with rest and rehab to make sure he's 100 percent healthy.
player_news.analysis: Gibbs remains on track to be fully healthy for the start of the season, but he'll likely miss some practice time and could sit out the remainder of the preseason.

player_news.title: Jahmyr Gibbs (hamstring) expected to be fine per Dan Campbell
player_news.description: Lions coach Dan Campbell said Jahmyr Gibbs' hamstring injury is "gonna be fine."
player_news.analysis: Gibbs went down with a hamstring injury in practice earlier in the week. Detroit will likely play it safe with him, but he remains on track to be healthy for the start of the season.

player_news.title: Jahmyr Gibbs - Limited concern from coach Campbell
player_news.description: Lions head coach Dan Campbell suggested Wednesday that he's optimistic about Gibbs' health after the running back suffered a hamstring injury in Monday's practice, Eric Woodyard of ESPN.com reports. "I think we're gonna be fine here," Campbell told 97-1 The Ticket Detroit. "So, I think we'll be good."
player_news.analysis: Campbell didn't get into details or provide a timeline for Gibbs, merely hinting at general optimism. Gibbs suffered the injury 27 days before Detroit's season opener Sept. 8 at the Rams, and while he's unlikely to practice for at least the next week or two, he seemingly has a chance to be ready for the rematch of last year's wild-card playoff game.

player_news.title: Nathan Peterman - Returns to Raiders
player_news.description: The Raiders signed Peterman to the training camp roster Tuesday, Vic Tafur of The Athletic reports.
player_news.analysis: Peterman was let go by the Saints on Aug. 2, and it didn't take long for the journeyman quarterback to catch onto another team. The 2017 fifth-round pick appeared in two games for the Raiders across 2020 and 2021. If Peterman wishes to secure a spot on Las Vegas' 53-man roster, he'll have to beat out Carter Bradley and Anthony Brown for the No. 3 emergency quarterback job behind Gardner Minshew and Aidan O'Connell.

player_news.title: Odell Beckham Jr. Still Not Running Routes
player_news.description: Miami Dolphins wide receiver Odell Beckham Jr. (undisclosed) signed with the team 97 days ago, but he remains on the Physically Unable to Perform list and has yet to resume running routes at training camp. Quarterback Tua Tagovailoa said he's thrown to Beckham over the last three months, but it's just been "spot catching, him getting to see the way the ball spins, get a feel of it." "I've got to see him catching and running routes with our guys first and getting into the mix first before I can say anything," Tagovailoa said. When healthy, the 31-year-old Beckham is expected to be the No. 3 or 4 wideout behind Tyreek Hill, Jaylen Waddle and Braxton Berrios, but the fact that he has yet to practice at all with the team with just three weeks until the regular-season opener isn't a good sign. As of right now, OBJ shouldn't be drafted in standard 12-team fantasy leagues.

player_news.title: Odell Beckham - Not yet running routes
player_news.description: Dolphins head coach Mike McDaniel said Wednesday that he's "not necessarily concerned" that Beckham (undisclosed), who remains on the active/PUP list, still isn't running routes, David Furones of the South Florida Sun Sentinel reports.
player_news.analysis: Beckham still has yet to practice three weeks into training camp, and the Dolphins seem to be considering him week-to-week due to an undisclosed issue. There's hope that Beckham will provide a boost in the passing game and finally give Miami a reliable No. 3 receiver behind Tyreek Hill and Jaylen Waddle (undisclosed), but the veteran will first need to get healthy and up to speed in a new offense.

player_news.title: Odell Beckham Jr. not running routes
player_news.description: Odell Beckham Jr. is not running routes in training camp with the Dolphins.
player_news.analysis: It is not clear what the injury is that Beckham is dealing with, but Dolphins coach Mike McDaniel said he is not concerned. It is unclear how long Beckham will be sidelined.

player_news.title: Daylen Baldwin - Lands in Arizona
player_news.description: The Cardinals signed Baldwin to a contract Tuesday.
player_news.analysis: Baldwin spent time with Atlanta earlier this offseason but was cut by the team early August. Now, the third-year pro gets a chance to compete in Arizona's wide receiver room. Baldwin appeared in one game with the Browns as a rookie in 2022, but he hasn't suited up for regular-season action since then.

player_news.title: T.J. Luther signs with the Steelers
player_news.description: The Steelers signed WR T.J. Luther.
player_news.analysis: Luther has yet to appear in an NFL regular season game. He was most recently waived by the Patriots. He'll compete for a depth spot in the Steelers wide receiver room.

player_news.title: T.J. Luther - Signs with Pittsburgh
player_news.description: Luther and the Steelers agreed on a contract Tuesday, Alan Saunders of SteelersNow.com reports.
player_news.analysis: Luther worked out for the Steelers on Aug. 4 and he'll now officially join the team at practice. The wide receiver could be a viable option as return specialist with Pittsburgh in 2024.

player_news.title: Bo Nix to take majority of first-team reps this week
player_news.description: Broncos QB Bo Nix is expected to take the majority of the first-team reps ahead of his start in the second preseason game.
player_news.analysis: Nix remains in a competition for the starting quarterback job for the Broncos. The first-round pick looked solid in his first NFL action against the Colts, completing 71.4% of his passes for 125 yards and a touchdown.

player_news.title: Rashod Bateman sees uptick in reps Tuesday
player_news.description: Rashod Bateman saw an uptick in reps at practice on Tuesday.
player_news.analysis: Bateman returned to practice on Monday with the Ravens where he did not do as much. He was able to slowly work his way back to doing more activity at practice on Tuesday.

player_news.title: Trace McSorley signs with Commanders
player_news.description: Trace McSorley has signed a deal with the Washington Commanders, per source.
player_news.analysis: McSorley joins the Commanders after rookie quarterback Sam Hartman was injured and unlikely to play in the Commanders' preseason game versus Miami. The Penn State grad will likely be the Commanders' fourth-string quarterback, and while he will play in the preseason, he likely won't be fantasy-relevant during the regular season as he is buried in the depth chart.

player_news.title: Christian Kirk not practicing Wednesday
player_news.description: Christian Kirk did not appear to be practicing on Wednesday.
player_news.analysis: Kirk was at the field, but did not have his pads on. It is unclear if it's related to an injury or if it's a day off.

player_news.title: Tarik Black - Waived/injured by Pittsburgh
player_news.description: Black was waived/injured by the Steelers on Tuesday with an undisclosed injury.
player_news.analysis: There is no word on the specific nature of Black's injury, nor the severity. If he ultimately goes unclaimed off waivers, the pass catcher would revert to Pittsburgh's injured reserve. From there, his season would be over unless both parties end up coming to terms on an injury settlement down the line. Black was competing with a plethora of receivers for a depth role prior to this move.

player_news.title: Xavier Legette (foot) participates in 7-on-7 drills with first-team
player_news.description: Xavier Legette was getting in 7-on-7 reps at practice on Wednesday.
player_news.analysis: Legette was working with the first-team at practice. He was listed as a backup on the initial depth chart, but still has time to earn his way into a starting role.

player_news.title: Carson Steele - Increased reps at RB
player_news.description: Steele had his most reps at running back with the first-team and second-team offensive units at practice Tuesday, Jesse Newell of The Kansas City Star reports.
player_news.analysis: Steele turned four carries into 29 yards and a touchdown in Saturday's 26-13 loss to the Jaguars, earning himself more opportunities with the top offensive packages. The 21-year-old took advantage of Clyde Edwards-Helaire (illness) missing another practice, seeing additional work over the likes of Deneric Prince and Keaontay Ingram according to Pete Sweeney of ArrowheadPride.com. Offensive coordinator Matt Nagy said Tuesday that Steele is "doing a lot of good things and being in the right spot at the right time, and that you can trust him." It's unclear what role Steele will have with the team in 2024, whether at running back or fullback, but he's doing a good job endearing himself to the coaching staff.

player_news.title: Mark Andrews Involved In Car Crash, Avoids Injuries
player_news.description: The Baltimore Ravens announced on Wednesday that tight end Mark Andrews was involved in a car accident while driving to the team's facilities. Andrews was evaluated by the medical staff and did not sustain any apparent injuries. He later joined the team for their morning meetings. Andrews was originally scheduled for a non-practice day on Wednesday and is expected to return to the field in the coming days. "I appreciate everyone's thoughts and well wishes. This is a great reminder about the importance of wearing seatbelts and remaining alert while driving a car," Andrews said in a statement. The 28-year-old's 2023 season ended early in Week 11 due to a lower-leg injury, but he's healthy now and will once again be one of quarterback Lamar Jackson's top targets in one of the most explosive offenses in football. Treat him as a top-five fantasy TE.

player_news.title: Mark Andrews - Seems uninjured after car accident
player_news.description: Andrews (undisclosed) was involved in a car accident Wednesday and did not sustain any apparent injuries.
player_news.analysis: Andrews joined team meetings Wednesday morning following the accident. The standout tight end was initially scheduled for a non-practice day Wednesday, and he's expected to retake the field "in the coming days." It appears that Andrews emerged from a potentially dangerous situation without serious aftereffects, and while the Ravens may opt for caution rather than rushing him back to practice, there doesn't currently seem to be any true concern about his health or upcoming availability. Baltimore will take on the Falcons at home in a preseason matchup Saturday.

player_news.title: Mark Andrews involved in car accident but uninjured
player_news.description: The Ravens announced Mark Andrews was involved in car accident but he was uninjured.
player_news.analysis: Andrews got into the accident when driving to practice Wednesday morning. He was not scheduled to practice on Wednesday. It is unclear how long he will be sidelined, but it appears he escaped anything too serious.

player_news.title: Mohamed Ibrahim - Receives full medical clearance
player_news.description: Ibrahim (hip) was cleared for football activity Tuesday, Jordan Schultz of BleacherReport.com reports.
player_news.analysis: Ibraham ended the 2023 season on the Lions' practice squad injured list with a hip injury he sustained in Week 7 against the Ravens. Now healthy, he'll look to catch on with a team in need of running back depth.

player_news.title: Antoine Green - Reverts to IR
player_news.description: Green (concussion) reverted to Detroit's reserve/injured list Tuesday after clearing waivers, per the NFL transaction log.
player_news.analysis: Green hauled in all three of his targets for 13 yards in Thursday's preseason game against the Giants before leaving due to a concussion he sustained on a block attempt in the second quarter. The 2023 seventh-round pick was getting reps with the Lions' first-team offense alongside wide receivers Amon-Ra St. Brown and Jameson Williams early in training camp. However, now that he's on IR, Green will be forced to miss the entire 2024 season unless he reaches an injury settlement with Detroit.

player_news.title: Brandon Aiyuk watches 49ers practice Wednesday
player_news.description: 49ers WR Brandon Aiyuk watched practice from the sidelines Wednesday.
player_news.analysis: Aiyuk continues to be the subject of trade conversations, most recently with the Steelers. It is notable that this was the first time he has watched practice in over a week and was wearing 49ers gear. The team has also reportedly increased their offer to the wide receiver, so there is a possibility that he could remain with the team if they can agree on a contract extension.

player_news.title: Brandon Aiyuk - Still talking with Niners
player_news.description: The 49ers are trying to work out a contract with Aiyuk but also have agreed to parameters of a trade with the Steelers, ESPN.com reports.
player_news.analysis: It's the latest turn in a lengthy, ongoing drama, with ESPN's Jeremy Fowler reporting that a trade to Pittsburgh is "one phone call away." The 49ers previously discussed deals with the Browns and Patriots, but reports suggested negotiations fell through due to Aiyuk's hesitance about signing a long-term deal with either team. He's apparently willing to go to Pittsburgh, which essentially leaves everyone waiting on the 49ers to either complete a trade or meet Aiyuk's contract demands. It's possible the Steelers eventually rescind their offer if San Francisco's front office continues to drag things out with the effort to convince Aiyuk to take less than what Pittsburgh is offering.

player_news.title: 49ers, Brandon Aiyuk Not Far Apart On Long-Term Deal
player_news.description: The saga involving the San Francisco 49ers and wide receiver Brandon Aiyuk may conclude in the coming days, as Mike Garafolo reports that the team hasn't pulled the trigger on a trade because a deal with Aiyuk that would keep him in San Francisco isn't far apart. It's also reported that Aiyuk would prefer to stay with the 49ers and has always preferred to stay with the 49ers, all things being equal. Aiyuk's status has made waves across the league over the past several days, but on the field, Aiyuk is one of the most efficient and productive wide receivers in the league. The 26-year-old Aiyuk would be a low-end fantasy WR1 upon a new deal with the 49ers, where he would retain his status as the top field stretcher in one of the NFL's best offenses.

player_news.title: Lucas Krull (toe) returns to practice Wednesday
player_news.description: Lucas Krull returned to practice on Wednesday after suffering a toe injury in Sunday's game.
player_news.analysis: Krull caught all four of his targets in the Broncos preseason opener. He is expected to compete for an immediate role in the tight end room for Denver.

player_news.title: Jeff Smith - Cut with injury settlement
player_news.description: The Cardinals released Smith (undisclosed) with an injury settlement Tuesday, per the NFL's official transaction log.
player_news.analysis: Smith spent the entire offseason with Arizona, but he appears to have picked up an undisclosed injury during training camp. The journeyman wideout will be eligible to sign with another club once healthy. He suited up for 11 regular-season games with the Jets last year, hauling in eight of 11 targets for 134 yards in that span.

player_news.title: Sterling Shepard - Dealing with undisclosed injury
player_news.description: Shepard, who did not play in Saturday's preseason opener against the Bengals, is dealing with an unspecified injury and didn't practice Monday, Scott Smith of the team's official site reports.
player_news.analysis: Smith notes the veteran wideout actually began missing practice time in the days leading up to the game versus Cincinnati. Shepard, who was a college teammate of Baker Mayfield, is expected offer veteran depth, although he may realistically serve as no more than a No. 5 receiver given the promising play of both rookie Jalen McMillan and second-year wideout Trey Palmer.

player_news.title: Bub Means - Participates in practice Tuesday
player_news.description: Means (undisclosed) donned a red non-contact jersey during Tuesday's practice session, John Hendrix of SI.com reports.
player_news.analysis: Means is dealing with an unspecified injury that held him out of Saturday's preseason contest against Arizona. The rookie fifth-rounder is battling for a depth spot at wide receiver, and his availability for the last two preseason games would play a big role in whether he makes the Saints' 53-man roster at the end of training camp.

player_news.title: Alvin Kamara - Remains sidelined Wednesday
player_news.description: Kamara (back) is not practicing Wednesday, Mike Triplett of NewOrleans.Football reports.
player_news.analysis: Kamara will miss a second consecutive day of practice due to back tightness. Coach Dennis Allen downplayed the severity of Kamara's situation Tuesday, so it doesn't appear the veteran running back is dealing with anything that will keep him from practicing for too long. If Kamara's back tightness keeps him off the field for Sunday's preseason game against the 49ers, though, it could pave the way for Jamaal Williams to start, especially with Kendre Miller (hamstring) still a non-participant.

player_news.title: Alvin Kamara Still Out Wednesday
player_news.description: New Orleans Saints running back Alvin Kamara (back) remained out of Wednesday's practice at training camp. Kamara is managing a back issue that he's dealt with in the past, and there appears to be a minimal amount of concern regarding the star back's health at this point. It's looking unlikely that he'll make an appearance in Sunday's preseason game against the hosting San Francisco 49ers, though. Kamara has plenty of risk in 2024 fantasy drafts while entering his age-29 season and witnessing his rushing efficiency decline in each of the last three years, but his role in New Orleans' passing game as quarterback Derek Carr's security blanket cannot be ignored. Last year, Kamara drew 87 targets despite missing four games via suspension, ranking third among RBs in full-PPR fantasy points per game (17.9). Until Kendre Miller (hamstring) is back at practice, Kamara remains a decent RB2 bet in fantasy.

player_news.title: Alvin Kamara Exits Practice With Back Tightness
player_news.description: New Orleans Saints running back Alvin Kamara (back) did not practice on Tuesday. Very little is known about the injury, but it is described as "back tightness". Kamara is in line for another large-volume season with the Saints. Jamaal Williams and Kendre Miller are in line for touches behind Kamara. However, when healthy, Kamara dominates the backfield touches for the Saints. Should this injury persist, then the Saints may be faced with the same inefficiencies they experienced from Williams and Miller when Kamara was suspended for the first three games of 2023. Fantasy managers should continue to check back to ensure that Kamara will not miss significant time.

player_news.title: Zach Charbonnet misses practice Wednesday
player_news.description: Zach Charbonnet did not practice on Wednesday.
player_news.analysis: Seahawks coach Mike Macdonald said Charbonnet was "tight" Wednesday morning.  "We're trying to figure out what's going on," Macdonald said.

player_news.title: Rakim Jarrett - Nursing unspecified injury
player_news.description: Jarrett did not practice Monday due to an undisclosed injury, Scott Smith of the team's official site reports.
player_news.analysis: The second-year wideout was able to log 31 snaps in the preseason-opening win over the Bengals on Saturday night, but head coach Todd Bowles confirmed Jarrett was a non-participant in the first practice following that contest. Bowles added Jarrett was "nursing an injury" without offering any more specifics, and it remains to be seen if the receiver will be able to participate in the first day of joint practices with the Jaguars on Wednesday.

player_news.title: John Wolford - Still has shot at No. 2 job
player_news.description: Wolford remains in a close competition with Kyle Trask for the No. 2 quarterback job, Scott Smith of the team's official site reports.
player_news.analysis: Wolford was the presumptive No. 3 quarterback throughout the offseason and heading into the first preseason contest, but the veteran journeyman played well throughout the second half of the exhibition win over the Bengals on Saturday night. Wolford spent some late-season time on the Buccaneers' practice squad in 2023, but with both him and Trask starting from scratch in new coordinator Liam Coen's scheme this offseason, it seems Wolford is doing enough to give himself a chance at the primary backup job.

player_news.title: Justin Watson - Could help fill in for Brown
player_news.description: Watson could see added early-season opportunities, with Marquise Brown dealing with a shoulder injury, Adam Teicher of ESPN reports.
player_news.analysis: With Brown -- whose availability to start the coming season unclear -- unable to practice, Teicher relays that Watson has been taking many of the snaps that would have otherwise gone to Brown.  While it remains to be seen if fellow wide receiver Rashee Rice will miss any time this season due to a potential suspension, it does appear in any event that Watson is a candidate to see increased snaps out of the gate this season pending Brown's status, with rookie Xavier Worthy additionally poised to factor in. Also in mix for WR depth chart slotting are Skyy Moore, Kadarius Toney, Justyn Ross, Mecole Hardman and Nikko Remigio

player_news.title: Justin Watson An Early Beneficiary Of Marquise Brown's Absence
player_news.description: The early beneficiary of Kansas City Chiefs wide receiver Marquise Brown's (shoulder) injury in training camp practices has been Justin Watson, who is taking many of the snaps that would have gone to Brown. Watson last year was tied for second among the team's receivers in catches with 27. With Brown's status up in the air for Week 1 against the Baltimore Ravens, KC may have to keep seven receivers to open the year. Others competing for roster spots include Mecole Hardman, Skyy Moore, Nikko Remigio and Justyn Ross. Hardman, Moore and Ross played for the Chiefs last year, but none of them were very consistent. Watson will see increased chances with Brown out, but rookie Xavier Worthy will be asked to be the team's big-play wideout, and he's the much better late-round target for fantasy managers.

player_news.title: Jordan Addison carted to the locker room at practice Wednesday
player_news.description: Vikings WR Jordan Addison was carted off the practice field Wednesday with an apparent leg injury.
player_news.analysis: Addison went down on the sideline and had to be helped off the field by the training staff. It appears to be a leg injury for Addison, but the Vikings will not know the severity until he undergoes further testing.

player_news.title: Jordan Addison - Leaves practice on cart
player_news.description: Addison (undisclosed) was carted off the field during Wednesday's practice, Alec Lewis of The Athletic reports.
player_news.analysis: After leaping for a contested pass, Addison was visibly hobbled as he left the field with help from the Vikings' training staff. The nature of his injury isn't yet known but likely will be clarified once coach Kevin O'Connell nexts talk to the media.

player_news.title: Tavon Austin Hangs Up His Cleats
player_news.description: Wide receiver Tavon Austin officially announced his retirement from the NFL on social media on Tuesday. Austin was originally drafted by the St. Louis Rams with the eighth overall pick in 2013 out of West Virginia. He spent the first five years of his NFL career with the Rams before playing for the Dallas Cowboys, Green Bay Packers and Jacksonville Jaguars. The 34-year-old hadn't appeared in an NFL game since 2021 with the Jags, when he caught 24 of his 37 targets for 213 yards and one touchdown in 13 games (three starts). The nine-year NFL veteran finished his career with a total of 244 catches on 407 targets for 2,239 yards and 16 touchdowns in 113 games (53 starts). Austin's two best seasons were in 2015 and 2016 with the Rams, when he combined for 982 yards and eight touchdowns.

player_news.title: Tavon Austin - Retiring from football
player_news.description: Austin announced his retirement Tuesday, ESPN reports.
player_news.analysis: Austin played in nine seasons in the NFL between four different teams and five different cities. While he never achieved a 1,000-yard receiving season, he provided memorable utility and energy as a ball-carrier throughout his tenure.

player_news.title: Tavon Austin announces retirement
player_news.description: Tavon Austin announced his retirement from the NFL after nine seasons.
player_news.analysis: Austin most recently played for the Jaguars during the 2021 season. He started his NFL career with the Rams during five seasons. Austin combined to record 3,600 yards from scrimmage with 26 total touchdowns.

player_news.title: Ben Mason - Waived with injury
player_news.description: The Steelers waived/injured Mason on Tuesday due to an undisclosed injury, per the NFL's official transaction log.
player_news.analysis: The Steelers have not provided much transparency regarding the specific nature of Mason's injury. Assuming he ultimately clears waivers, the fullback would subsequently revert to the team's injured reserve. From there, his season would be done unless both he and Pittsburgh can reach an injury settlement once his health is back up to par.
